description.text:
This is Day 5 of my collection of printable equations. To see the whole collection, go to: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:227210 For today's equation, I'm revisiting the Archimede's spiral (r = atheta) of day #3 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:228425). A variant is Fermat's spiral, r = +/-atheta^0.5 (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_spiral). In contrast to Archimede's, Fermat's spiral exhibits a flat region near theta = 0 and a continuously decreasing distance between turns. It also, to the best of my knowledge, has no practical application. But it looks cool. Details:
  • units are in mm
  • curve thickness was reduced from 5 to 3 mm to avoid overlap.
  • a = 1.5 (to give a diameter of 100 after 3 turns)
  • Range(theta) = 0 to 1080
  • stl resized to make x axis = 100 mm
    • As always, I'm going to continue to post one equation per day until get bored or people lose interest. If there's a particular equation you'd like to see, leave a comment and I'll give it a shot.
All files can be printed without support. Photos shown were printed on a Replicator 2 and sliced using the standard setting on Makerware.

comments.text: Fermat's Spiral is useful since it can be used to evenly space objects with respect to angle, especially when the Golden Angle is used...   Put a point every 137.508 degrees and a very regular-looking pattern will result (though it always looks wonky right in the middle).  They've used it to place mirrors for solar collectors and such things.

description.text:
A fully tested and working (including auto bed leveling geometry and cooling fan airflow path) toolhead mount for the E3D Titan Aero!

Designed to be as light as possible (but still structurally rigid), I've gotten some awesome prints out of this design.

I highly recommend the Cura 2 Alpha from Lulzbot so you can save your nozzle size in your machine profile and swap between it like any other toolhead: https://code.alephobjects.com/project/profile/10/

A lighter toolhead allows the operator to operate at higher acceleration, jerk and speed - allowing for either faster prints or higher print quality at stock settings. Personally I leave settings at default other than jerk which I set to 20~30 for more dimensionally accurate corners and easier parts that fit together (Lulzbot really needs to add LIN_ADVANCE to their firmware).

Design files available upon request. Designed in Fusion 360. Message me with your F360 registered email to be added to the repo.

Pancake steppers can NOT drive 3mm filament, even at 1A of current. Get a half height NEMA 17 such as Moon's. ESteps should be around ~417.

4x M8 locknut for those wood bolts + 4xm8 washer

description.text:
Basically I went nuts when I got my Anet A8 and started printing upgrades and accessories right away. After printing cable chains for the Extruder and heated bed I noticed that nobody had made or at least published a thing for a Z-axis cable chain and then I decided to make my own.

I had already printed an electronics case and was planning on making the mosfet case since I already had the mosfet boards ordered from a certain online web-store.

Also I had a bed cable chain and an extruder cable chain so I thought to myself, how could I use the things I already had printed and design a cable chain for the Z-axis so my printer could have a more uniform look instead of random hanging cables in a sleeve.

The answer was to modify the Mosfet case's cover and the X-motor side attacment of the extruder cable chain.

Note 1: I printed total of 16 chain links.

Note 2: If you make this thing you will need to extend your cables for the following parts or they will not be long enough to connect to the Anet A8 motherboard.

  • X-axis stepper motor
  • X-axis end limit switch
  • Extruder stepper motor
  • Extruder heater
  • Extruder temperature sensor
  • Extruder stepper motor cooling fan
  • Extruder nozzle cooling fan

Prepare yourself for some serious soldering! :)

title: 28mm Motor Mount and Nosecone for GWS Formosa/HK "Patternish Ship"

description.text:
This is a nosecone and motor mount for installing a standard 28mm OD motor on a GWS Formosa or the Hobbyking clone, which is called the F3A "Patternish Ship" (terrible name, I know). It was designed to be printed with the "front" section against the print bed. I printed it in ABS, although PLA should be fine too if you don't crash. The final weight (not including the motor) was around 68g, but thinning the walls or decreasing the fill would lower that further.

I am using a 28-26 motor in the 250w range, and the cowl flows more than enough air to keep it nice and cool. A longer motor would also work. Two motor mount holes 16mm apart, and the other two are 19mm apart. You may need to rotate the mounting hole pattern so the motor wires line up with the channel designed into the side of the motor bay, but any of Hobbyking's NTM Propdrive motors should line up correctly.

description.text:
Been using Gregs Wades Ultimate Extruder ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:961630 ) and so far i'm very happy with it. I've had to modify very little (basically added a portion for my proximity sensor), however I never got any of the flexible filament mods to work reliably until i created my own. This version is meant to be a replacement filament guide for this extruder. I'm working on a completely from scratch extruder using this principle but not relying as heavily on PTFE tubing.

Pictures show the issue as well as my solution. Another thing i wasn't entirely enthusiastic about was having to unscrew (all the way) the idler screws half the time to change filament. I love the design that jonaskuehling made so this is where i started from. The overall idea was to minimize the space around the hobbed bolt for flexible filament to, possibly, buckle. Notice the PTFE, as one piece, is trimmed (using dremel or hobby knife) to have a notch cutout roughly the same size as the pinch diameter of the hobbed bolt. This idler has been filled in and a slightly oversized hole is cut through to allow for the other end of the ptfe to stick through. As usual (with my E3dv6) the PTFE continues all the way down to the heat break where it rests.

The idler screws are now definitely just for tension as changing filament is a breeze. Back out (spinning large gear) any filament left, then simply insert your new filament (rigid/flexible) in to the top of the ptfe until it rests against the hobbed bolt. Spin the big gear and it will grab and start feeding downward.

Final note: i've been little by little testing increasing speeds at which flexible is printed, please let me know how high you can get yours!

Notes:

This print will need supports but just the minimum under each 'ball bearing'
If you printer isn't set up correctly, especially over extruding, it will render the bearing fused together.

You will need to 'break' the ball bearings away from the cage.
Use a small pointed blade/screwdriver to get between two balls and twist to break the connection with the outer cage.
Do that all the way around the bearing and it will start to rotate.
Add fine oil/Vaseline to lube and the more you play with it the smoother it will rotate!
However, if your printer supports are too dense or your printer is over-extruding then it may be fused too much.
Aim for an under extrude setup if you have no luck with standard settings.

description.text:
These 3 parts (makes 4 pieces) replace the existing ones to adapt it to use a standard 60mm Fan. No holes are printed into the adapter and must be drilled since each fan mount is a little different. The fan mount itself is different and positions the fan higher than the original 40mm.
The new fan must be mounted on top in order to have bed clearance, so you must also print 2 copies of the Fan brackets since they allow the fan to be mounted on top and adjust the fan angle slightly up.
There is no need to replace the 40mm fan, there is no added benefit unless you are switching to a more powerful fan. I damaged my original fans sockets during original assembly and decided to use this to replace it with some of the dozens of existing 60mm ones I have in the scrap pile. I really recommend using a half height "thin" fan. I have been using a 12v .22a Evercool Half Height CPU cooling fan with no problem.

If your printer is calibrated correctly, these parts will fit snugly together. Mine managed to snap together and have held for a few days printing with no glues or other adhesives.(so far!)
If your printer is slightly out of calibrations, you may need to shape pieces with sandpaper/files and/or use adhesives (like the originals)
You need to print 1 of each of the 3 parts except for the fan bracket, you will need two pieces to complete this part.
When you have the 2 fan brackets and the fan swivel, insert them exactly as the originals. They will initially be a very tight fit and may need to be forced. Then you will need to rotate the swivel, which will loosen up quickly and self adjust to the fit.
Mount this assembly onto the 60mm Fan Base. You may need to sand or shape the pieces to fit and may need glue or adhesive to hold it. If it is a tight fit, like mine, just press real hard and the friction fit will hold it together without the need for adhesives.
Place your fan right on the top of the fan brace (NOT underneath as in the original!) with the edges pressed tight against the flat edges of the fan brackets. Then drill the screw holes that match your specific fan holes alignments. Start with a drill bit smaller than your actual screws so they will have something to grab onto.
That's it. Attach your fan and your are ready to go!
Make sure that your controller board or power supply can handle the difference if you alter the stock setup. Altering the electronics may damage and mostly like will void any warranty on your 3d printer!

To insert the platforms into the body, I found it easier to slightly angle the platforms toward the top or bottom of the body. This will help you get one of the top/bottom edges of the platform inserted.

The platform pieces fit EXTREMELY snug into the body, so just be careful when inserting. It takes quite a bit of pressure, but not so much that you are breaking the model :)

description.text:
I made a housing for a touchscreen with a mount for the Raspberry Pi to serve as an Octoprint Controller. I keep it next to my 3d Printer for easy local control. It's super handy.

Check out my post about it here: http://www.candlercustoms.com/3d-printed-octoprint-controller/

Printer:

Tevo Black WIdow

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

20%+

Notes:

I almost always run a wide nozzle. For this print I was using a .8mm nozzle and at .4 layer heights and it was still an ~11 hour print, but it came out awesome. I use the heck out of this thing.

Supports are pretty minimal, only the span across the front for a switch and the mounts. I used PLA; I haven't found the heat to be too much for it.

I re-uploaded the files to use readily available terminal blocks and a toggle switch. I also added an alternate file with a blank front and top, labeled as AltBlank.

(Sorry for the weird orientations, I'm having a hard time with the CAD export orientation relative to Thingi's orientation.)

Equipment Used
  • Prepare Octoprint on existing Raspian install. Instructions here: http://octoprint.org/download/
  • I also installed TouchUI as an add-on (I alternate between using it or not because I like the full access of the regular view.)
  • Mount the barrel connector into the slot; it's intentionally a pretty tight fit.
  • Use distribution block or lots of wire twisting to provide voltage for raspi, touchscreen and fan.
  • Add front Switch if you'd like (I use it to turn off the screen and raspi when i'm not planning on printing for a while)
  • Mount the fan (if you decide to use one, I'm not sure how entirely necessary it is to have one.
  • Pre-mount the daughterboards on the VGA Adapter STL.
  • Slide the VGA Adapter board STL with all mounted equipment and toucscreen itself into front slots.
  • Insert the two HDMI ends through the top and connect before fully connecting top to rest of box.
  • Flip the switch and enjoy local control!!

Links shown for convenience. Full disclosure: These will give me a small kickback from Amazon and will help me recoup the extra spool of filament I used prototyping this thing. Thanks a ton y'all.
